      {
        "id": 2997,
        "name": "Alex Miller",
        "username": "alexmiller",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/alexmiller/{size}/326_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-01-12T02:52:57.801Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I missed that <a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/john_brownlee\">@john_brownlee</a> responded on the issue you filed instead.  I\u2019ll copy it here, as he did the work so his answer is more accurate than mine:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I decided not to use fdbmonitor in the interest of having each container run as few things as possible. For running backup agents, I think that the best approach would be to run a separate container for them. I think the main advantage that fdbmonitor would provide in a dockerized environment would be to support bouncing the fdbserver processes in a fast and coordinated way to pick up new arguments or (especially) to upgrade FoundationDB. Doing that would require a way to change the monitor conf file without bouncing the container, and that will likely depend on features that are specific to a deployment platform, so I figured they were out of the scope of the initial work.</p>\n</blockquote>",
